    <item>
      <title>Simulating Load on a File-System</title>
      <link>http://0.0.0.0:1313/2012/11/14/simulating-load-on-a-file-system/</link>
      <pubDate>Wed, 14 Nov 2012 12:27:22 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>http://0.0.0.0:1313/2012/11/14/simulating-load-on-a-file-system/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;a&#xA;&#xA;&#x9;&#xA;&#x9;&#xA;&#x9;&#x9;href = &#34;/img/2012/11/load.jpg&#34;&#xA;&#xA;&#x9;&#x9;&#xA;&#xA;&#x9;&#xA;&#xA;&#x9;&gt;&#xA;&#x9;&#xA;&#x9;&lt;span&gt;&#xA;&#x9;&#x9;&lt;img src=&#34;http://0.0.0.0:1313/img/2012/11/load.jpg&#34; alt=&#34;load&#34;&gt;&#xA;&#x9;&lt;/span&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Sometimes you want an easy way to simulate load on a file-system that you are trying to test. Here&amp;rsquo;s a quick and easy way.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Suppose your mount point you want to perform this IO is &amp;ldquo;/myspecialmount&amp;rdquo;. (Assuming you have plenty of space to test)&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Then the easiest way to load some IO is through the following bash-script:&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;[sourcecode language=&amp;ldquo;bash&amp;rdquo;]&#xA;#!/bin/bash&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;while true&#xA;do&#xA;echo &amp;ldquo;=== Starting clean-up ====&amp;rdquo;&#xA;rm -fr /myspecialmount/usr&#xA;echo &amp;ldquo;=== Starting load ====&amp;rdquo;&#xA;rsync -avp /usr /myspecialmount&#xA;done&#xA;[/sourcecode]&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>How to list the package contents of a yum install?</title>
      <link>http://0.0.0.0:1313/2011/12/25/how-to-list-the-package-contents-of-a-yum-install/</link>
      <pubDate>Sun, 25 Dec 2011 16:43:03 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>http://0.0.0.0:1313/2011/12/25/how-to-list-the-package-contents-of-a-yum-install/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;Sometimes you need to see what&amp;rsquo;s installed as part of a package via yum. To see the package contents you can use a utility that&amp;rsquo;s available on the RHEL/CentOS.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;[sourcecode language=&amp;ldquo;jscript&amp;rdquo;]&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;$repoquery &amp;ndash;list &lt;strong&gt;packagename&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;[/sourcecode]&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;If you do not have this utility available, you can install it by using this command&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;[sourcecode]&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;$yum install yum-utils&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;[/sourcecode]&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Here is a sample output from looking at the package contents of Apache httpd.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
